s and outs of production methods, timber milling, and forest custodianship in diverse corners of the world, including the Pacific Northwest, Madagascar, Spain, Brazil, Germany, Japan, China, Hawaii, and Australia. They unlock surprising insights into longer arcs of world history: on the human exploitation of nature, colonialism, industrial capitalism, cultural tensions, and seismic upheavals. But the authors also strike a hopeful note, offering a parable of wider resonance—of the incredible but underappreciated skill and care that goes into growing forests and felling trees, milling timber, and making enchanting musical instruments, set against the human tendency to reform our use (and abuse) of natural resources only when it may be too late. The Guitar promises to resonate with anyone who has ever fallen in love with a guitar.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGuitar makers. 0aGuitarxConstructionxEnvironmental aspects. 0aGuitarxConstruction. 0aLogging. 0aLumber trade. 0aWood. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aenvironmental studies, music education, biological sciences, trees, botany, guitar factories, port cities, travel writing, environmentalism, log booms, remote sawmills, wood, indigenous lands, rainforests, behind the scenes stories, musical instruments, interviews, first-hand account, production methods, timber milling, forest custodianship, pacific northwest, madagascar, spain, brazil, germany, japan, china, tourism, hawaii, australia, exploitation of nature, colonialism.1 aWarren, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226764016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226764016/original  a978-3-11-07